### Boolean Type

The `bool` type represents Boolean values with two possible states: `true` and `false`.

```dart
void main() {
  bool isActive = true;
  bool isComplete = false;

  print(isActive);   // true
  print(isComplete); // false
}
```

### Boolean Operators

```dart
void main() {
  bool a = true;
  bool b = false;

  print(a && b);  // false (AND - both must be true)
  print(a || b);  // true  (OR - at least one true)
  print(!a);      // false (NOT - inverts)
}
```

### Comparison Operators (return bool)

```dart
void main() {
  int x = 10;
  int y = 5;

  print(x == y); // false
  print(x != y); // true
  print(x > y);  // true
  print(x < y);  // false
  print(x >= y); // true
  print(x <= y); // false
}
```

### Conditional Expressions

```dart
void main() {
  bool isLoggedIn = true;

  // if-else
  if (isLoggedIn) {
    print('Welcome!');
  } else {
    print('Please log in');
  }

  // Ternary operator
  String message = isLoggedIn ? 'Welcome' : 'Please log in';
  print(message);
}
```

### Truthy and Falsy

Unlike JavaScript, Dart does NOT treat non-boolean values as truthy or falsy.

```dart
void main() {
  String? name;

  // This will NOT compile:
  // if (name) { ... }

  // Must use explicit boolean check:
  if (name != null && name.isNotEmpty) {
    print('Name: $name');
  }

  // Dart 3 logic operators with patterns
  if (name case var n? when n.isNotEmpty) {
    print('Name: $n');
  }
}
```

> **Key Point:** In Dart, only `bool` values can be used in conditional contexts. You cannot write `if (name)` - you must write `if (name != null)`.

